Project: Console Aerospace Simulator (C++17), 1D simulation (vertical only)

What you are building (keep it concrete)
    A console-based rocket/satellite simulator that:
        Simulates motion (altitude, velocity)
        Applies forces (gravity, thrust, drag)
        Uses interchangeable physics algorithms
        Prints telemetry in real-time
        Accepts commands (launch, pause, adjust thrust)

What to experiment with (this is where learning happens)
    Don’t just run it—play with it:
        1. Change thrust
            SetThrustCommand thrustCmd(5000);   // rocket may fall
            SetThrustCommand thrustCmd(20000);  // strong lift
        2. Change mass
            rocket.state.mass = 500;
        3. Break it intentionally
            Set thrust = 0 → free fall
            Negative thrust → force downward

Next step (worth doing immediately)
    Add drag—this is where it starts feeling real:
        Inside computeAcceleration:

            double drag = 0.01 * rocket.state.velocity * rocket.state.velocity;
            drag *= (rocket.state.velocity > 0 ? -1 : 1);

            return thrustAcc - g + drag;

        Now you’ll see:
            Rocket slows down at high speed
            More realistic motion

One honest note
    Right now this is 1D simulation (vertical only). That’s fine.
    But real aerospace simulation =
        vectors (x, y, z)
        orientation (quaternions)
        forces in 3D
    Don’t jump there yet—this 1D model is exactly how professionals start prototyping.

Future work
    Add Runge-Kutta integrator (huge learning jump)
    Add fuel consumption
    Add stage separation (event system)

